We start by extracting the key figures using the “End_amount” values provided:

1. Current Assets and Current Liabilities  
 • Total Current Assets = 8,810,936.45  
 • Total Current Liabilities = 2,491,297.55  
  → Current Ratio = Total Current Assets / Total Current Liabilities  
   = 8,810,936.45 / 2,491,297.55 ≈ 3.54

2. Gross Profit Margin  
 • Gross Profit = 1,535,951.24  
 • Total Revenue = 7,825,951.24  
  → Gross Profit Margin = (Gross Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
   = (1,535,951.24 / 7,825,951.24) × 100 ≈ 19.63%

3. Debt to Asset Ratio  
 From the balance sheet, total liabilities consist of the current liabilities only:  
 • Total Liabilities = 2,491,297.55  
 • Total Assets = 14,089,860.66  
  → Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets  
   = 2,491,297.55 / 14,089,860.66 ≈ 0.18

4. Net Profit Margin  
 • Net Profit = –1,401,436.89  
 • Total Revenue = 7,825,951.24  
  → Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
   = (–1,401,436.89 / 7,825,951.24) × 100 ≈ –17.91%

5. Cash to Current Debt Ratio  
 • Ending Cash and Cash Equivalents = Sum of Cash on Hand and Bank Deposits  
  = 1,753,673.43 + 1,522,888.62 = 3,276,562.05  
 • Total Current Liabilities = 2,491,297.55  
  → Cash to Current Debt Ratio = Cash / Current Liabilities  
   = 3,276,562.05 / 2,491,297.55 ≈ 1.32

6. Free Cash Flow (FCF)  
 Typically, FCF = Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities – Capital Expenditures  
 • Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –4,398,760.38  
 • Purchase of Fixed Assets (CapEx) = 324,677.57  
  → FCF = –4,398,760.38 – 324,677.57 = –4,723,437.95

7. Return on Assets (ROA)  
 • ROA = (Net Profit / Total Assets) × 100  
  = (–1,401,436.89 / 14,089,860.66) × 100 ≈ –9.95%

Thus, the final answer is:

  }
